\begin_layout Standard
The map that that acts as the shift operator for continued fractions is
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor \label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, if one writes out the continued-fraction expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x=\frac{1}{a_{1}+\frac{1}{a_{2}+\frac{1}{a_{3}+\cdots}}}\equiv\left[a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\cdots\right]\]

\end_inset

then one has that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h(x)=\left[a_{2},a_{3},\cdots\right]\]

\end_inset

whence the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shift operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This map is often called the Gauss Map.
 Note that shift operators, as linear operators, are studied as a subtopic
 of Banach theory, and often appear in applied mathematics texts devoted
 to the engineering topics of control theory, stability theory and filter
 design
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Part2004"

\end_inset

.
 However, in these texts, shift operators are typically applied to sequences
 of functions defined on Hardy spaces.
 It appears that the shift as applied to continued fractions is very nearly
 unstudied -- and no wonder -- it appears nearly intractable when approached
 with standard analytic tools.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron or transfer operator associated with the Gauss
 map is known as the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing (GKW)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kuzmin1928,Wirsing1974"

\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 It is the pushback of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and as such, is a linear map between spaces of functions on the unit interval
 (topological vector spaces).
 That is, given the vector space of functions from the closed unit interval
 to the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{F}=\left\{ f\,|\, f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}\right\} \]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 .
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, it is represented by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+x)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)\label{eq:sum-form}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This operator has not been 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solved
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in the sense that there is no known closed-form analytic solution expressing
 its all of its eigenfunctions and eigenvectors.
 There is one classically known eigenvector, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=1/(1+x)$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to the unit eigenvalue; this solution was given by Gauss.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kuzmin considers iterating this operator, and shows that given any continuous,
 differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 with bounded derivative on the unit interval, that the iterate converges
 uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=C/(1+x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, by defining 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{k+1}(x)=\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}g_{k}\right](x)\]

\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}(x)\to C/(1+x)$
\end_inset

 uniformly, for all bounded, differentiable 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, as a corollary, this eigenvector is unique
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "section 15"
key "Khin35"

\end_inset

.
 An alternative way of understanding this result is via the Frobenius-Perron
 theorem, which asserts that the eigenfunction associated with the maximal
 eigenvalue is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from this one analytic solution, there is a large class of fractal,
 discontinuous-everywhere functions associated with eigenvalue 1.
 The prototypical such solution is the derivative of the Minkowski Question
 Mark function 
\begin_inset Formula $?(x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}?^{\prime}\right](x)=?^{\prime}(x)\]

\end_inset

A proper construction for the everywhere-discontinuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and the derivation of the above identity, is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

, together with a construction of a class of other similar solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operator is not normal (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}\mathcal{L}_{h}^{T}$
\end_inset

 is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}^{T}\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

); this is typically the case for transfer operators.
 Thus, the left and right eigenvectors are distinct, although they share
 common eigenvalues (technically, these should be called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular values
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, although we will persist in calling them eigenvalues below; and likewise
 diagonalization should properly be called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

singular value decomposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and the left and right eigenvectors are properly called the left and right
 singular vectors.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When considering a basis where the right-hand-side eigenvectors are smooth
 (differentiable), then the operator has a discrete spectrum (as is typically
 the case for transfer operators).
 The first eigenvalue below 1.0 is approximately 0.3036, and is known as the
 GKW constant [xxx need ref here].
 As is typically the case for transfer operators, when the right eigenvectors
 are smooth functions, then the left eigenvectors are linear combinations
 of derivatives of Dirac delta functions, located at 0 and 1.
 All of this is explored in greater detail, in the rest of this paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relation to the Riemann Zeta Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gauss map is connected to the Riemann zeta function by a Mellin Transform:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}h(x)\, x^{s-1}dx\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Riemann zeta can be written under a change of variable as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}dx\; x\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{s-1}\right]\label{eq:zeta-gkw}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and thus it seems that a better understanding of GKW may shed light on the
 Riemann Hypothesis and/or the Berry conjecture.
 Most immediately, simple manipulations lead to a representation for the
 Riemann zeta in terms of binomial coefficients.
 This relation is explored in detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-zeta2004,Fla06"

\end_inset

; it leads to criteria that are shown to be equivalent to the Riemann Hypothesis.
 The same development can be used to obtain Dirichlet L-functions, and generaliz
ations to other number-theoretic series, such as the totient series, or
 the Liouville series 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-norlund-2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

