\begin_layout Subsection
Lack of simple solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from the classical solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1+x)$
\end_inset

, there do not seem to be any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

easy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 polynomial series solutions to the operator, where a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be a closed-form specification of the eigenvectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The author performed a combinatorial search of simple combinations and summation
s of rational functions and various classical functions, such as the exponential
, the gamma, the digamma, the dilogarithm, Bessel functions and the exponential
 integral.
 No eigenvalues were found in this way, although, of course, various close
 approximations can be so obtained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The naivest approaches to solving the GKW operator, which is suggested by
 the eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sum-form"

\end_inset

, is blocked by the next two theorems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
There is no (non-trivial) polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\tau)$
\end_inset

 such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(\frac{1}{\tau+n}\right)=\lambda_{n}\left(\tau+n\right)^{2}f\left(\tau\right)\]

\end_inset

 holds for all integer values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and arbitrary values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume that there does exist such a solution.
 Then it could be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(\tau\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}a_{k}\tau^{k}\]

\end_inset

for some unknown values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 (which are independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 Inserting this into the hypothetical form leads to the equation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\lambda_{n}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\tau^{k}\left[a_{k-2}+2na_{k-1}+n^{2}a_{k}\right] & =\\
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\tau^{k}\frac{\left(-1\right)^{k}}{n^{k}}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}{j+k-1 \choose j-1}\frac{1}{n^{j}}\end{align*}

\end_inset

Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=1$
\end_inset

 in the above allows it to be re-written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda_{n}\left(n-1\right)^{2}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\left(-1\right)^{k}a_{k}=a_{0}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}n^{-k}\sum_{j=0}^{k}{k \choose j}\, a_{j+1}\]

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 are independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by assumption, one must then have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, and for each term in the series on the right hand side, one must have,
 individually, that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0=\sum_{j=0}^{k}{k \choose j}\, a_{j+1}\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the theorem is proved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Were it not for this theorem, a solution would have been provided by looking
 for quasi-modular-form-like functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Another naive avenue is also blocked: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
There is only one series solution to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f\left(\frac{1}{\tau+n}\right)=\frac{\left(\tau+n\right)\left(\tau+1\right)}{\left(\tau+n+1\right)}\lambda f\left(\tau\right)\]

\end_inset

and it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\tau\right)=a_{0}/\left(1+\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
As in the previous proof, assume a series solution.
 Substituting this into the above, and performing a straightforward but
 tedious expansion in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and then comparing terms, reveals that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=\left(-1\right)^{k}a_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the above had allowed solutions for something other than 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, then one would have also had that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=\lambda f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Assorted Algebraic Identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section lists an assortment of random algebraic results, none particularly
 deep; some are vaguely suggestive of deeper relations.
 These are listed here mostly for the sake of completeness.
 These are the sorts of identities one obtains by means of knuckle-headed
 persistence in the hope that that maybe one little algebraic twist will
 yield a closed-form solution.
 These were obtained by the author long before he knew that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 had a name or had been previously studied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we notice that adjacent terms in the series can be made to cancel
 by shifting the series by one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x)-\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x+1)=\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which holds for any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x).$
\end_inset

 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}\rho=\lambda\rho$
\end_inset

, then it would also solve 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}\rho\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)=\lambda\left(\rho(x)-\rho(x+1)\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can be solved easily to get the zeroth eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{0}(x)=\frac{1}{\ln2}\;\frac{1}{1+x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathcal{L}_{h}\rho_{0}](x)=\rho_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 and the normalization is given by requiring 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}\rho_{0}(x)\, dx=1\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can see one hint of the relationship between period-doubling and the
 GKW in the identity 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{1+x}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{2^{n}}\left[\frac{2}{x+n}-\frac{1}{x+n+1}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A reflection identity: 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=1-(1+x)^{-2}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=1-f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}[(1+?(x))/(1+x)^{2}]=1-?(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $?(x)$
\end_inset

 is the Minkowski Question Mark function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}[?(x)\, x^{-2}]=2-?(x)$
\end_inset

 .
 One can construct a variety of identities of this sort, for example: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{h}\left[?(x)\left(\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}-2\right)\right]=\frac{?(x)-2}{(1+x)^{2}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

but these types of exercises do not seem to lead to any sort of worthwhile
 recurrence relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acting on the monomial, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{k}\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{k+2}}=\frac{(-)^{k+2}}{(k+1)!}\psi^{(k+1)}(1+x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{(k)}(x)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th derivative of the Gamma function.
 The true difficulty of finding the solution to GKW becomes clear when the
 search leads one to start discovering complicated identities, such as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{m^{2}}\psi^{(1)}\left(1+\frac{1}{m}+x\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{2}}\psi^{(1)}\left(\frac{1}{n+x}+1\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

or to finding curiosities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+ax)^{2}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=\psi^{(1)}(1+x+a)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+nx)^{-2}-1$
\end_inset

 one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=-\sum_{k=1}^{n}(x+k)^{-2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acting on a general power, the map gives the Hurwitz Zeta: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{s}\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{s+2}}=\zeta_{H}(s+2,x+1)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This allows eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zeta-gkw"

\end_inset

 to be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}dx\; x\zeta_{H}\left(s+1,x+1\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further consideration leads to various conditionally convergent series:
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}\,\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\zeta(k+m+2)=1\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which holds for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Additional series, similar to the form given above, are possible, and are
 reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-A&S-Anno"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, for example, one has:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}\,\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m+1\end{array}\right)\zeta(k+m+2)=\zeta(m+2)-1\]

\end_inset

 We also have series such as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}e^{-tk}=\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)e^{-tk}=\frac{3}{4}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)(k+3)e^{-tk}=\frac{7}{4}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)(k+3)(k+4)e^{-tk}=\frac{45}{8}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}(k+2)(k+3)(k+4)(k+5)e^{-tk}=\frac{93}{4}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Its not clear what the general expression for forms of the above type is.
 Similarly, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{m}\equiv\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}\frac{(k+m+1)!}{(k+1)!}\left[\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right]e^{-tk}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

then we find 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}=1/2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}=1/4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}=1/4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}=3/8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}=3/4$
\end_inset

 but its again not clear what the general expression might be.
 The above sums are generated by considering 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi(1+z)=\frac{-1}{1+z}+1-\gamma+\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}(-)^{m}\left[\zeta(m+2)-1\right]z^{m+1}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and then writing 
\begin_inset Formula \[
z^{m+1}=(z+1-1)^{m+1}=\sum_{k=0}^{m}(-)^{m-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
k\end{array}\right)(z+1)^{k}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function for the moments of the Minkowski Question Mark
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Alkauskas2007,Alkauskas2007a,Alkauskas2008"

\end_inset

 participates in a curious identity.
 This generating function obeys the relation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{z^{2}}G\left(\frac{1}{z}\right)+\frac{1}{\left(z+1\right)^{2}}G\left(\frac{1}{z+1}\right)=\frac{1}{z\left(z+1\right)}\]

\end_inset

which holds for complex-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (such as, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto z+n$
\end_inset

), and also 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{1}{z}+\frac{1}{z^{2}}G\left(\frac{1}{z}\right)=G\left(z\right)-2G\left(z+1\right)\]

\end_inset

From this, one has the curious shift-over-by-one relationship 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}G\right]\left(z\right)=G\left(1+z\right)+\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}K\right]\left(z\right)\]

\end_inset

 where we've defined 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(z\right)=G\left(1+z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polynomial Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can attempt to solve GKW by working in the polynomial representation.
 One possible choice is to make one's Taylor expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, but this turns out to be a very poor choice, as we shall soon see.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}f=g$
\end_inset

 and substituting a Taylor's expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!}f^{(k)}(0)\]

\end_inset

and likewise for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{g^{(m)}(0)}{m!}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}\,(-)^{m}\;\frac{(k+m+1)!}{m!\,(k+1)!}\,\zeta(k+m+2)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, adopting the bra-ket notation introduced earlier
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-B04"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle m\left|\mathcal{L}_{h}\right|k\right\rangle =(-)^{m}\;\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta(k+m+2)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we've replaced the factorials by the binomial coefficient that they
 form.
 Unfortunately, this is clearly a very poorly conditioned matrix.
 One can make some progress, if one wishes, by applying a regulator and
 using Levin-type sequence acceleration techniques.
 One can thus find a number of curious identities, some of which we've listed
 previously.
 However, the difficulty of working with divergent sums seems to outweigh
 any advantages given by the relatively simple form of the matrix elements.
 Thus, one is lead to consider the matrix elements for a polynomial expansion
 about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 These are far more complex, but give a very well-conditioned matrix.
 These are: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{mn}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\left[\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right]\label{eq:GKW-matrix-elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(-)^{m}\frac{g^{(m)}(1)}{m!}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}(-)^{n}\frac{f^{(n)}(1)}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Other authors have chosen to expand about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Briggs2003"

\end_inset

 but it would appear that expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 leads to the simplest tractable expansion.
 The general case, of a Taylor's expansion about some fixed point, is explored
 in the appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first eigenvalue is known as the GKW constant, and is about 0.3036.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenvector equation to be solved is then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}v_{n}=\lambda v_{m}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\{v_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector with components 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This beast has a discrete spectrum (need reference for proof), and so we
 may label the eigenvalues and eigenvectors with a label 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th eigen equation is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}v_{nk}=\lambda_{k}v_{mk}\label{eq:Eigenvalue eqn}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th polynomial eigenfunction of the GKW operator is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}v_{nk}(1-x)^{k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The zeroth eigenfunction was given by Gauss as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{0}(x)=\frac{1}{1+x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and corresponds to the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n0}=2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Again, we note the curious appearance of powers of two.
 Graphs of the first few eigenvectors are shown in figure 
