\begin_layout Subsection
Identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the identity
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}p^{-n}=p\left[\zeta(m+1)-1-\zeta_{H}\left(m+1,2+\frac{1}{p-1}\right)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

, the right hand side equals 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{-m}$
\end_inset

; this corresponds to the known eigenvector.
 Note that for any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the leading term on the right is 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-(m+1)}$
\end_inset

.
 A simple way to arrive at this is to note that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p^{-n}(1-x)^{n}=\frac{p}{p-1+x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and then evaluate this simple expression under the action of the GKW operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Kernel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We would like to know what the kernel of the GKW operator is.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k(x)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}\exp(2k+1)\frac{\pi}{x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}k\right](x) & = & \exp\left((2k+1)\pi x\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\cos(2k+1)n\pi\nonumber \\
 & = & \exp\left((2k+1)\pi x\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}(-)^{n}\label{eq:}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The value of the sum is ambiguous.
 One is tempted to cancel terms pairwise, and thus declare 
\begin_inset Formula $k(x)$
\end_inset

 to belong to the kernel.
 On the other hand, the regularized sum is not zero: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}e^{-tk}=\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and so one is left in a bit of a quandary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some progress might be made by applying the theory of the Henstock-Kurzweil
 integral.
\end_layout

